\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Obtain Data}

\subsubsection{\textbf{Data Sourcing}}

This work integrates three complementary data sources. The HAI (HIL-based Augmented 
ICS) Security Dataset, version 23.05~\cite{HAI-Dataset-v4.0}, constitutes the primary 
empirical data source. The testbed faithfully replicates three interconnected 
real-world industrial processes --- a boiler, a turbine, and a water treatment unit --- 
coupled to a HIL simulation of a steam/hydro turbine and power grid model, as 
illustrated in the process flow diagram of the testbed (Figure \ref{fig:digital_twin_hai}). The physical architecture comprises tanks (TK01--TK04),
heat exchangers, pumps, and valves. Collected at 1\,Hz, the dataset captures the
complete operational state across four signal categories: process variables (PVs) 
including pressure (\texttt{P1\_PIT01}), water level (\texttt{P1\_LIT01}), flow rate 
(\texttt{P1\_FT03Z}), and dual temperature readings (\texttt{P1\_TIT01}, 
\texttt{P1\_TIT03}); control variables (CVs) encoding actuator commands such as valve 
positions and pump setpoints; setpoints (SPs) representing desired reference values; 
and auxiliary plant signals providing operational context. Each observation carries a 
binary attack flag indicating whether an attack is active. The categorical scenario 
labels used for model conditioning were derived by extracting the defining features of 
each attack type from the HAI~23.05 technical documentation~\cite{HAI-Dataset-v4.0} 
and mapping them to a four-class scheme based on attack mechanism and process condition: 
normal operation (class~0), Actuator Pollution without combustion (class~1), Actuator 
Pollution with combustion (class~2), and Actuator Emulation without combustion 
(class~3). The attack model, illustrating the points within a control loop at which an 
adversary may manipulate setpoints, process variables, control variables, or control 
parameters, is shown in Figure~\ref{fig: HAI 23.05}

