Less than 1\% of data that was missing due to errors or missing readings. Linear interpolation was used to rebuild these gaps in the signal, resulting in a continuous signal. Next, a \texttt{StandardScaler} is fitted exclusively on normal-only samples from the training 
portion, ensuring that the normalization statistics reflect legitimate plant behavior 
and are not distorted by attack dynamics. Columns with variance below $10^{-8}$ are 
automatically removed to prevent numerical instability before normalization. Sliding windows of 300 
timesteps (5 minutes) input and 180 timesteps (3 minutes) target are then extracted 
with a stride of 60 seconds. A stride of 60 seconds was chosen to ensure that any attack event will happen in one window instead of being split. The input window of 300\,s was selected to span 
approximately eleven times the longest causal lag identified in the process graph 
(26\,s for \texttt{P1\_TIT03} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{P1\_PP04D}), ensuring the model 
observes sufficient process history to capture the slowest plant dynamics. The 
prediction horizon of 180\,s was chosen to cover the mean attack duration observed 
in the HAI~23.05 dataset (213--221\,s across test segments), ensuring the model's 
output window captures the bulk of a typical attack's effect on process variables. 
