The input feature space is defined by a physics-informed decomposition of the HAI
testbed into its constituent control loops and physical plant~\cite{homaei2026cdt},
without any manual feature engineering. Plant inputs consist of all sensor channels
after removing the five PVs. Controller inputs are limited to the setpoint (SP),
process variable (PV), and control variable (CV) for each respective loop,
re-normalised using a per-loop \texttt{StandardScaler} fitted only on normal training
samples to prevent attack dynamics from distorting the normalisation statistics.



\subsection{Model Design \& Selection}
\subsubsection{\textbf{overview}} The digital twin must predict future process variable (PV) values across a multi-loop industrial control system, under both normal operation and active attack scenarios. This requires a model that can capture sequential temporal dependencies, handle multiple interacting control loops, and generalise across operating conditions with fundamentally different dynamics.

A data-driven sequence modelling approach was adopted over physics-based alternatives for two reasons: the HAI boiler system involves complex nonlinear interactions between pressure, flow, level, and temperature that are difficult to model analytically; and the availability of labelled historical data with attack scenarios makes supervised learning the most direct path to scenario-aware prediction.

Among sequence model families — LSTM, GRU, and Transformer — GRU was selected following empirical comparison. LSTM's cell state adds parameter overhead without meaningful gain at the timescales of this system. The Transformer architecture struggles with the long autoregressive rollout required at inference, accumulating error over the prediction horizon. GRU provides the best trade-off between temporal memory, parameter efficiency, and stable autoregressive rollout.

The system was modelled as a closed loop: separate GRU controller models predict actuator outputs (CVs) per control loop, which feed into a shared GRU plant model that predicts all sensor outputs (PVs). This mirrors the actual DCS structure — controllers and plant are distinct functional blocks — and allows each component to be trained and evaluated independently before closed-loop composition. The overview architecture is shown in \ref{fig:OVERVIEW ARC ITECTURE}.

