\paragraph{\textbf{CCSequenceModel.}}
The cooling loop (CC) controls a digital pump with discrete on/off 
behaviour and continuous speed, requiring a specialised output structure. 
The model shares the same encoder-decoder backbone as GRUController but 
replaces the single output head with two parallel heads: a binary 
classifier head producing a pump on/off logit, and a regression head 
predicting pump speed. Both heads are trained jointly, with binary 
cross-entropy loss on the classifier and mean squared error on the 
regressor.

\paragraph{\textbf{Closed-loop composition.}}
At inference, the five controller models predict their respective CV 
sequences independently. These predicted CVs are injected into the plant 
model's target-window input, and the GRUPlant rolls out the full PV 
prediction horizon autoregressively. This mirrors the physical DCS structure in which controllers and plant 
are distinct functional blocks. The closed-loop dynamics are captured 
implicitly through training on historically observed DCS data; at 
inference, controllers and plant run independently with no runtime 
feedback between them.

\subsection{Algorithmic Approach}

\subsubsection{\textbf{Training Pipeline}}

Training proceeds in two sequential stages. In Stage~1, the causal plant model
is trained from a warm-started baseline. In Stage~2, the Stage~1 checkpoint is
fine-tuned with per-scenario loss weighting to improve reproduction of attack
dynamics. Controllers are trained jointly alongside the plant in both stages
but are never retrained between stages. The full pipeline is summarised in
Figure~\ref{fig:training_pipeline}.

